@article{Hotz:1965b,
	Abstract = {In Part I the theory of X-categories was developed, which enable us to give the problems arising in connection with the synthesis of switching circuits an algebraical form. The system of primitive building blocks was represented by the generator system cal{A} of a free X-category $F(\cal{A})$. Each of the elements of $F(\cal{A})$ represents the synthesis of a circuit from the primitive building blocks and each synthesis of a circuit has a correspondence in $F(\cal{A})$.
In Part II we adapt the theory more to the technical reality. Let b A, B, $\in F(\cal{A})$ and A' resp. B' the circuit designated by A resp B. $A\circ B$ represents the circuit which arises from A' and B' by switching the output number i of B' on the input number i of A. The circuits can be switched in another way too: On can switch the i-th output of B' on the $i_k$-th input of B', where $i \rightarrow i_k$ is a permutation. Beyond it, it is possible to connect one output of B' with two or more inputs of a circuit A' or not to use any output. We take account of this technical self-evidence and take three elements V, D, U into A and fix their functions such that V represents the crossing of tow wires and D the branching of a wire in tow branches. U represents an element k which has one input but no output.
Now the following problem arises. Let be $A,B\in F(\cal{A})$. One finds a system of relations R that allows transforming A into B if and only f A and B realize the same function for each coordination of functions to the elements of $\cal{A}\{U<V<D\}$. 
This problem is solved in this paper for the special case, that the elements of $\cal{A}\{U<V<D}$ have only one output. Forming equivalence classes respective R one gets the quotient category m which is a free d-category (category with the direct product).
This result is of interest for the automatic modifying of programs in computers too.},
